When we use mirror joints, we first need to make sure the controls are zeroed out, meaning the joints have zero rotation values. Then, we set the mirror function as behavior, meaning the newly generated joints would have orientations that make them perform mirror action when the same value is applied. For example, a positive z value would have this affect (moving outward) for both arms, instead of the right fk arm (newly generated joints) moving towards the left side/inward. This is a more useful or intuitive way of manipulating joints. And using the mirror joint function with the ik joints would create new ik handles that are corresponding to the newly generated joints, so those new ik handles do work, but we need to put them to the right place and delete the old ones.Â 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Those are for the joints, for the controls, what do we do? We can put a group on top of whatever control group we have. Because the new group would have its pivot in world origin, we can set the scale x value to -1 to mirror those controls over. However, we can notice that the controls have different orientations from those of the joints. Should we use parent constraint to change the orientation? The answer is no when using behavior mirror function, and we mirror the controls using the method we just mentioned.
